top.value: This Indefinite Delivery, Indefinite Quantity (IDIQ) Contract for Energy Sector Technical Assistance (TA), Feasibility Studies (FS), and Sector Planning Missions (SPMs) will improve the efficiency and efficacy of USTDA's project planning assistance by developing a pool of highly qualified technical experts to undertake energy-specific TAs, FSs, and SPMs.

This $655,188 feasibility study (FS) evaluated train control and rail signaling systems in Kazakhstan. The FS studied three rail corridors (from Shymkent to Zhangaqazaly, Zhangaqazaly to Qandyaghash, and Almaty to Aqtoghay) that KazakTemirZholy, the Grantee, considers representative of its national rail network.

A USTDA grant to Green Liquified Natural Gas Limited is funding a feasibility study that would assess the viability of a 144 tons per day liquefied natural gas liquefaction and distribution facility and associated regasification and distribution stations in Southwestern Nigeria.

This grant funds a feasibility study for PT Nusatama Properta Panbil (NPP), a private conglomerate in Indonesia, to develp a liquefied natural gas (LNG) bunkering and breakbulk terminal on Asam Island in the Malacca Strait. The goal of the feasibility study is to assess the market opportunity and initiate the legal documentation for development of the LNG terminal.

This technical assistance grant provides funding for a Procurement Advisor with two Sector Procurement Experts (Advisors) to assist the Philippines Department of Transportation (DOTr). The grant represents Phase III of the Procurement Assistance Program for the Philippines under the Global Procurement Initiative: Understanding Best Value (GPI). The Advisors provide strategic and technical procurement advice on transportation sector procurements, with the goal of incorporating value-based methodologies into DOTr's procurement process. A value-based procurement system will help implement sustainable, high-quality transportation projects and may increase opportunities for U.S. companies to bid on and potentially win transportation tenders.

USTDA's will partially fund a technical assistance to design the optimal airspace, runway approaches and air traffic control operating procedures for the New Istanbul Airport. The New Istanbul Airport is scheduled to open in 2018 and when completed in 2024, it will be one of the largest in the world, hosting 150 million passengers annually on flights to more than 350 destinations. Accordingly, GA Havaliman Iletmesi A.. (IGA), the concessionaire that will operate the airport for 25-years, is seeking technical assistance to ensure that the airspace operates at sufficient capacity to meet the anticipated traffic demand on the opening day in 2018.
